  "type": "mcq",
  "marks": 1,
  "readingTitle": "Misconception check",
  "reading": "<p><strong>❌ Common misconception:</strong> \"The dresses are elastic.\" / \"Haddock is inelastic.\"</p><p><strong>✅ The correct idea:</strong> Goods are not elastic — DEMAND for them is price elastic or price inelastic. OCR put an 'Assessment for Learning' warning in a real mark scheme about this exact sloppiness: candidates who wrote 'dresses are elastic' or 'demand falls a lot' instead of 'demand for dresses is price elastic, so a price rise causes a proportionally larger fall in quantity demanded' lost credit. Always name the concept in full: <em>demand for X is price elastic/inelastic</em>.</p>",
  "question": "Which sentence uses the terminology correctly?",
