  "pageId": "economics:3-4-price-stability",
  "pageName": "3.4 Price Stability",
  "source": "tips",
  "type": "mcq",
  "marks": 1,
  "readingTitle": "calculation — Calculations: compound it, and sign it",
  "reading": "<p>Three rules cover every calculation here:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Inflation compounds — apply rates one at a time.</strong> £45 × 1.04 × 1.05 = £49.14, NOT £45 + 9%.</li>\n<li><strong>Real = nominal − inflation.</strong> 1.6% − 2.6% = −1%. The mark scheme gives the 1st mark for '1' and the <strong>2nd mark ONLY if BOTH the negative sign AND the % sign</strong> are present.</li>\n<li><strong>Best deal for a lender</strong> = highest REAL return, not highest nominal. 5% with 1% inflation (+4%) beats 7% with 4% inflation (+3%).</li>\n</ul>",
